00:05:57.974 --> 00:05:59.966
[END PLAYBACK]

00:05:59.966 --> 00:06:04.450
[APPLAUSE]

00:06:04.450 --> 00:06:07.150
- So in a few moments,
Gabrielle and Jen

00:06:07.150 --> 00:06:10.480
will speak to you in greater
detail about the movie

00:06:10.480 --> 00:06:14.830
and the interplay of gender
and drag performance.

00:06:14.830 --> 00:06:19.720
And you'll be treated to
some terrific performances

00:06:19.720 --> 00:06:21.610
by our artists.

00:06:21.610 --> 00:06:24.910
But I want to conclude with a
third and more general lesson

00:06:24.910 --> 00:06:29.350
that the encounter with
drag might teach us.

00:06:29.350 --> 00:06:32.500
And that's a lesson
about latent,

00:06:32.500 --> 00:06:34.062
unrecognized possibilities.

00:06:34.062 --> 00:06:35.770
And here I'm going to
introduce something

00:06:35.770 --> 00:06:44.950
that I'm sure you never
expected in an event on drag.

00:06:44.950 --> 00:06:48.640
Drag invites us, I
think, to ask what if?

00:06:48.640 --> 00:06:52.060
What if we tried something
that we never, not only never

00:06:52.060 --> 00:06:55.780
tried before, but never
even thought of trying.

00:06:55.780 --> 00:07:00.790
What wonderful new truth about
the world, about ourselves

00:07:00.790 --> 00:07:02.830
might we discover?

00:07:02.830 --> 00:07:04.550
Now, I want to illustrate this--

00:07:04.550 --> 00:07:07.090
and this is the
unexpected part--

00:07:07.090 --> 00:07:11.830
with a simple example
about something

00:07:11.830 --> 00:07:13.330
that probably most
of you have never

00:07:13.330 --> 00:07:17.740
tried and certainly
not tried in connection

00:07:17.740 --> 00:07:20.620
with reflections on gender.

00:07:20.620 --> 00:07:26.650
The thing I have are paper.

00:07:26.650 --> 00:07:27.900
Everybody has paper.

00:07:27.900 --> 00:07:30.830
Everybody's handled
strips of paper.

00:07:30.830 --> 00:07:33.420
But have you ever thought
about the potential

00:07:33.420 --> 00:07:36.360
of two strips of paper?

00:07:36.360 --> 00:07:39.000
Think, you could have all
sorts of associations.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:42.300
One is sex, sexuality.

00:07:42.300 --> 00:07:51.007
One is John and Joanna, John and
Mary, the body and performance.

00:07:51.007 --> 00:07:52.590
There are all sorts
of things that one

00:07:52.590 --> 00:07:56.080
could associate with these two.

00:07:56.080 --> 00:08:01.390
Now, if you were to take
a strip of paper and glue

00:08:01.390 --> 00:08:05.170
them together and then cut
them, what would you get?

00:08:05.170 --> 00:08:06.490
You'd get two rings.

00:08:06.490 --> 00:08:08.580
Everybody knows this.

00:08:08.580 --> 00:08:12.080
But here's something that
probably you have never tried.

00:08:12.080 --> 00:08:20.830
Suppose you have two strips and
you glue them together and then

00:08:20.830 --> 00:08:23.328
what you can do--

00:08:23.328 --> 00:08:28.850
let's see here-- in terms
of unexpected possibilities.

00:08:28.850 --> 00:08:31.610
This is something that you
can try at home, right?

00:08:31.610 --> 00:08:33.169
It's PG.

00:08:33.169 --> 00:08:35.934
No, no, you can do it
with four year olds.

00:08:39.170 --> 00:08:41.150
Sorry.

00:08:41.150 --> 00:08:50.430
So you're going to
glue one and the other

00:08:50.430 --> 00:08:56.400
so that you end up
with two rings, right?

00:08:56.400 --> 00:08:57.390
Simple enough.

00:08:57.390 --> 00:09:00.780
Definitely try this at home.

00:09:00.780 --> 00:09:04.620
Now, before, if we had one
ring and we cut it apart,

00:09:04.620 --> 00:09:06.180
you know you get two rings?

00:09:06.180 --> 00:09:10.330
What happens if I now
take this and split

00:09:10.330 --> 00:09:13.953
this does anybody know?

00:09:13.953 --> 00:09:16.370
Again, it's not something that
you do every day, you know?

00:09:16.370 --> 00:09:18.130
It's not part of
your daily practice.

00:09:21.030 --> 00:09:22.835
Oh, let's see if I can cut this.

00:09:26.780 --> 00:09:33.480
You get one ring, four
rings, anything else?

00:09:39.840 --> 00:09:43.840
Any other takers
before I finally--

00:09:43.840 --> 00:09:48.315
So we have four rings, you have
one ring, but what do you get?

00:09:57.560 --> 00:09:58.723
You get a square.

00:09:58.723 --> 00:10:02.430
[APPLAUSE]

00:10:02.430 --> 00:10:03.900
Who'd have thought it, right?

00:10:09.410 --> 00:10:11.925
So we had two straight
rings, and we got this.

00:10:15.280 --> 00:10:17.280
I just wanted to show.

00:10:17.280 --> 00:10:19.313
I just sort of lost track.

00:10:22.070 --> 00:10:23.840
See how user friendly we are?

00:10:23.840 --> 00:10:28.160
We want to make sure that
you're able to do this at home.

00:10:28.160 --> 00:10:29.540
So you just saw the result.

00:10:29.540 --> 00:10:33.330
Now, we're going to
a second possibility.

00:10:33.330 --> 00:10:34.970
So now you get,
oh, maybe there's

00:10:34.970 --> 00:10:38.090
something more to these
ordinary strips of paper

00:10:38.090 --> 00:10:39.640
than you thought.

00:10:39.640 --> 00:10:43.490
And you think, OK,
now I know I can

00:10:43.490 --> 00:10:48.110
try something different, which
is you take two cross strips

00:10:48.110 --> 00:10:52.890
and you make one ring, but the
second time you add a twist,

00:10:52.890 --> 00:10:54.340
right?

00:10:54.340 --> 00:10:56.870
You add a twist.

00:10:56.870 --> 00:11:00.940
So again, you can imagine, OK,
sex, sexuality, John and Jen,

00:11:00.940 --> 00:11:03.550
there are all sorts of
variations you could think of.

00:11:03.550 --> 00:11:06.340
So this time, instead of
just two straight rings,

00:11:06.340 --> 00:11:09.980
you're going to get
one with a twist.

00:11:09.980 --> 00:11:11.705
So what is the result
of that process?

00:11:15.500 --> 00:11:18.506
Any takers here?

00:11:18.506 --> 00:11:21.260
- A tetrahedron.

00:11:21.260 --> 00:11:25.100
- Tetrahedron?

00:11:25.100 --> 00:11:29.570
Somebody who knows a lot
about geometry, but not really

00:11:29.570 --> 00:11:30.928
about sex.

00:11:30.928 --> 00:11:34.344
[LAUGHING]

00:11:39.720 --> 00:11:42.190
So again, don't
take my word for it.

00:11:42.190 --> 00:11:42.750
Try it.

00:11:45.330 --> 00:11:49.560
What you get,
interestingly enough--

00:11:49.560 --> 00:11:57.900
whoops-- is again, you'll get
a square, even with a twist.

00:12:00.770 --> 00:12:04.410
So final experiment-- think, OK,
that's been going pretty well.

00:12:10.170 --> 00:12:14.750
This time we're going
all the way, right?

00:12:14.750 --> 00:12:21.100
We're going to go and
make two interlinked rings

00:12:21.100 --> 00:12:25.910
with one twisted toward
the right and one

00:12:25.910 --> 00:12:28.990
twisted toward the left.

00:12:28.990 --> 00:12:30.702
What's going to happen?

00:12:30.702 --> 00:12:32.055
- A square.

00:12:32.055 --> 00:12:33.408
[LAUGHING]

00:12:33.408 --> 00:12:36.270
- Oh, OK.

00:12:36.270 --> 00:12:38.709
So, a pessimist.

00:12:38.709 --> 00:12:42.132
[LAUGHING]

00:12:45.555 --> 00:12:48.000
[INAUDIBLE]

00:12:58.280 --> 00:13:01.100
It doesn't look like it's
going to be a square.

00:13:05.150 --> 00:13:06.400
What is it going to look like?

00:13:06.400 --> 00:13:06.970
Let's see.

00:13:06.970 --> 00:13:08.756
Just got a little-- oops.

00:13:08.756 --> 00:13:09.780
My finger is stuck here.

00:13:18.850 --> 00:13:24.525
If you unfold it, what you find
is basically two linked hearts.

00:13:28.340 --> 00:13:30.265
And I think this
is a good lesson.

00:13:30.265 --> 00:13:34.450
[APPLAUSE]

00:13:34.450 --> 00:13:36.450
Now, what I'd like you
to think about is this,

00:13:36.450 --> 00:13:38.610
paper is such a simple thing.

00:13:38.610 --> 00:13:40.140
It only has two sides.

00:13:40.140 --> 00:13:42.670
Anybody can use this, right?

00:13:42.670 --> 00:13:45.020
Human beings are so
much more complicated

00:13:45.020 --> 00:13:46.870
than a two-sided sheet of paper.

00:13:46.870 --> 00:13:49.670
Think of the possibilities.

00:13:49.670 --> 00:13:52.450
So that's one of the
themes of this evening.

00:13:52.450 --> 00:13:57.253
I'd like now to turn it
over to Jen and Gabrielle.

00:13:57.253 --> 00:14:00.634
[APPLAUSE]

00:14:03.049 --> 00:14:05.470
- Thank you so much.

00:14:05.470 --> 00:14:06.940
- Thank you so much, Hisa.

00:14:06.940 --> 00:14:09.180
That was so wonderful.

00:14:09.180 --> 00:14:10.355
So I'm Jennifer Burton.

00:14:10.355 --> 00:14:11.980
And this is my sister
Gabrielle Burton.

00:14:11.980 --> 00:14:14.240
And we are two of
the five sisters.

00:14:14.240 --> 00:14:16.730
We have a company Five
Sisters Productions.

00:14:16.730 --> 00:14:20.990
We've made seven feature films,
many commercials, shorts,

00:14:20.990 --> 00:14:25.690
and including many that look
at gender from different angles

00:14:25.690 --> 00:14:26.830
and perspectives.

00:14:26.830 --> 00:14:29.380
We've made the MTV
LOGO film Happiest

00:14:29.380 --> 00:14:33.850
Day of His Life, which is
the picture-perfect wedding

00:14:33.850 --> 00:14:37.070
all gender reversed.

00:14:37.070 --> 00:14:40.260
We're making a series of short
films called Half the History

00:14:40.260 --> 00:14:43.390
on the under-told stories of
women in American history.

00:14:43.390 --> 00:14:47.230
We have a new film coming
out that's about parenting

00:14:47.230 --> 00:14:48.130
and gender.

00:14:48.130 --> 00:14:50.830
And, of course, Kings,
Queens, &amp; In-Betweens.

00:14:50.830 --> 00:14:53.570
Tonight, I also wanted to add,
is a particularly celebratory

00:14:53.570 --> 00:14:54.070
night.

00:14:54.070 --> 00:14:59.200
We're very happy to be kicking
off the 2019 conference.

00:14:59.200 --> 00:15:01.270
And also tonight one
of our performers

00:15:01.270 --> 00:15:04.450
in the film, Nina West, is
premiering on the RuPaul drag

00:15:04.450 --> 00:15:06.640
show.

00:15:06.640 --> 00:15:09.178
So that's exciting.

00:15:09.178 --> 00:15:09.970
- Hashtag teamnina.

00:15:13.570 --> 00:15:15.490
So we made this
film because we were

00:15:15.490 --> 00:15:18.550
interested in capturing gender
diversity and the complexity

00:15:18.550 --> 00:15:22.120
of gender performance
both on and off stage.

00:15:22.120 --> 00:15:25.870
Drag is a perfect window to open
up these questions about how

00:15:25.870 --> 00:15:28.900
we define identity in our
society, how we might get

00:15:28.900 --> 00:15:34.090
beyond the binaries of, say,
male-female, straight-gay,

00:15:34.090 --> 00:15:36.850
masculine-feminine and
instead create space

00:15:36.850 --> 00:15:41.390
to recognize the complexity
of all of our humanity.

00:15:41.390 --> 00:15:44.420
Using music and
costumes and movement,

00:15:44.420 --> 00:15:48.560
drag goes beyond words to
explore new possibilities

00:15:48.560 --> 00:15:51.070
for the aesthetics of gender.

00:15:51.070 --> 00:15:53.890
And so much of gender is
communicated non-verbally.

00:15:53.890 --> 00:15:55.750
We'd like to start
by introducing you

