00:20:08.820 --> 00:20:11.720
- Some of our greatest
chefs and cooks are men.

00:20:11.720 --> 00:20:14.560
But at the same time, they'll
tell you in the household,

00:20:14.560 --> 00:20:16.120
in a heterosexual
relationship, it

00:20:16.120 --> 00:20:17.500
should be the woman that cooks.

00:20:17.500 --> 00:20:19.923
Now, how do you
make sense of that?

00:20:19.923 --> 00:20:20.590
- You know what?

00:20:20.590 --> 00:20:21.490
I'm a guy.

00:20:21.490 --> 00:20:22.570
And I am feminine.

00:20:22.570 --> 00:20:24.070
And I have the right
to be feminine.

00:20:24.070 --> 00:20:25.270
And there's nothing
wrong with that.

00:20:25.270 --> 00:20:26.110
And I am a guy.

00:20:26.110 --> 00:20:28.360
I don't have to be your
stereotype of a guy.

00:20:28.360 --> 00:20:29.860
Even in the trans
community, there's

00:20:29.860 --> 00:20:32.590
a lot of expectations there
of what you're supposed to be.

00:20:32.590 --> 00:20:34.340
And I have people
telling me all the time,

00:20:34.340 --> 00:20:36.215
why are you messing it
up for the rest of us?

00:20:36.215 --> 00:20:38.950
People look at you and they
see you with your pink hair

00:20:38.950 --> 00:20:41.680
and acting like a girl
and that tells people

00:20:41.680 --> 00:20:44.170
that being a trans guy isn't
real and that you're faking it

00:20:44.170 --> 00:20:46.210
and that you're messing it up.

00:20:46.210 --> 00:20:50.740
And then it's like, what can
you say to that except I'm just

00:20:50.740 --> 00:20:52.220
trying to live my life.

00:20:52.220 --> 00:20:56.230
- The root of a lot of
violence and bullying and stuff

00:20:56.230 --> 00:20:59.290
like that is not about
sexual orientation.

00:20:59.290 --> 00:21:02.590
It's about gender identity
or gender expression.

00:21:02.590 --> 00:21:06.250
I mean, cultural expectations
that, if you have a vagina,

00:21:06.250 --> 00:21:07.950
you will be a female.

00:21:07.950 --> 00:21:10.330
You will then have a
certain kind of femininity,

00:21:10.330 --> 00:21:14.140
and then, you know, certain
jobs and certain power dynamics

00:21:14.140 --> 00:21:17.710
and certain relationships to
someone of the opposite sex who

00:21:17.710 --> 00:21:19.470
has a penis and all
of the expectations

00:21:19.470 --> 00:21:20.470
that go along with that.

00:21:20.470 --> 00:21:25.240
And people who don't follow
those rules get pushed around.

00:21:25.240 --> 00:21:27.370
And it happens on the
playground when you're five.

00:21:27.370 --> 00:21:29.980
And it happens in the
corporate world when you're 50.

00:21:29.980 --> 00:21:33.703
- But the binary of
gender maintains things

00:21:33.703 --> 00:21:35.370
like the census, where
you have to pick,

00:21:35.370 --> 00:21:39.670
are you a man or a woman,
are you male or female.

00:21:39.670 --> 00:21:41.780
But there are
obvious alternatives.

00:21:41.780 --> 00:21:43.420
Like, we could ask
people, where do you

00:21:43.420 --> 00:21:45.340
sit on the spectrum
or a continuum

00:21:45.340 --> 00:21:47.800
between masculine and feminine?

00:21:47.800 --> 00:21:51.340
- Super feminine, super butch,
I think there's a lot of us

00:21:51.340 --> 00:21:54.290
out there that just kind
it fall in the middle.

00:21:54.290 --> 00:21:56.590
- What comes to mind for
me is going to the bathroom

00:21:56.590 --> 00:22:05.040
in a public place as a woman
who reads as masculine often,

00:22:05.040 --> 00:22:09.138
I've had years of stares and
gasps and, [GASPS] are you

00:22:09.138 --> 00:22:09.930
in the right place?

00:22:09.930 --> 00:22:11.097
You know that kind of thing.

00:22:11.097 --> 00:22:15.000
But no woman responds
with violence towards me.

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:17.423
They respond with like
shock or something.

00:22:17.423 --> 00:22:18.840
- You kind of watch
over your back

00:22:18.840 --> 00:22:20.580
to see what's
happening behind you,

00:22:20.580 --> 00:22:22.830
you know, if you're walking
down the street, you know?

00:22:22.830 --> 00:22:25.680
Even though nothing would ever
happen and nothing ever has,

00:22:25.680 --> 00:22:29.370
you always are kind of keeping
an eye open, you know, to--

00:22:29.370 --> 00:22:31.130
- I wouldn't say
nothing ever happened.

00:22:31.130 --> 00:22:33.450
- No, I mean, you know,
people will yell something.

00:22:33.450 --> 00:22:34.260
But I'll tell you--

00:22:34.260 --> 00:22:35.280
- You got egged.

00:22:35.280 --> 00:22:37.500
- But not in drag.

00:22:37.500 --> 00:22:42.090
I think you have more
problems just as a gay man

00:22:42.090 --> 00:22:43.620
than you do as a drag queen.

00:22:43.620 --> 00:22:47.020
- When people think of sex and
gender, it's black and white.

00:22:47.020 --> 00:22:51.120
And for me, drag is a way
to show the gray areas.

00:22:51.120 --> 00:22:52.620
Because it's not
black and white.

00:22:52.620 --> 00:22:54.300
It's never been black and white.

00:22:54.300 --> 00:22:57.210
- The really fun part of
drag is playing around

00:22:57.210 --> 00:22:58.890
with what gender can mean.

00:22:58.890 --> 00:23:01.110
I can have, like, a
package in my pants

00:23:01.110 --> 00:23:02.940
and still not be bound.

00:23:02.940 --> 00:23:05.190
- You can be this masculine
person who is this

00:23:05.190 --> 00:23:08.310
male-identified character,
yet the male character that

00:23:08.310 --> 00:23:10.800
you're identifying
is really femme.

00:23:10.800 --> 00:23:13.860
- Once he starts singing, it
drops all gender barriers.

00:23:13.860 --> 00:23:15.960
- It's the freedom of drag.

00:23:15.960 --> 00:23:18.690
And I don't have to
be a man to do drag.

00:23:18.690 --> 00:23:19.930
I don't have to be a woman.

00:23:19.930 --> 00:23:21.120
I just have to be me.

00:23:21.120 --> 00:23:24.766
And I really think that's
what the essence of drag is.

00:23:24.766 --> 00:23:27.206
